on and Its Effects -- tChapter 13 A “Just War”? A Further Reassessment of the Alliterative Morte Arthure -- tChapter 14 Waging Spiritual War: Philippe de Mézières, The Order of the Passion and the Power of Performance -- tChapter 15 Christine de Pizan’s Epistre a la reine: A Woman’s Perspective on War and Peace? -- tChapter 16 Armed Conflict as Deadly Sin: Michel Beheim’s Verses on Wrath (1457–ca.1470) -- tChapter 17 Love and War in the Fifteenth Century Burgundian Prose Cligés: The Duke of Saxony’s Passion for Fenice -- tChapter 18 Sailing Away from Byzantium: Renaissance Crusade Literature and Peace Plans -- tChapter 19 The Art of Defying the Enemy: Albrecht Dürer’s Concept of the Ars fortificatoria -- tChapter 20 Sixteenth Century Protests Against War and Its Tragic Consequences: The Testimony of Hans Sachs and His Contemporaries -- tChapter 21 Racine’s Holy Wars -- tChapter 22 Out of the Kitchen and into the Fire: The Dutch Heroine Tradition -- tChapter 23 The Animal Actor and the Spectacle of Warfare: Lewis’s Timour the Tartar at Covent Garden -- tList of Illustrations -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributors to the present volume examine, from a wide variety of perspectives, the issues of war and peace in the Middle Ages and early modern time, probing the direction of the relevant discourse regarding the legitimacy and justification of military operations. Because man is a deeply aggressive and greedy creature, wars have been waged throughout times. Nevertheless, we can identify many voices in medieval literature, theology, philosophy, and in chronicle literature that questioned the validity and effectiveness of war, while many others argued for the traditional knightly ideals or called for crusades against the infidels. Those heroes who defend a people against an evil threat enjoyed profound respect, but there were also those figures calling for peace and the end of all fighting. As this volume demonstrates, war and peace have fundamentally determined medieval and early modern culture.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCivilization, Medieval. 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, Moderny15th and 16th centuriesxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, Moderny17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, Moderny18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aWar and literature. 0aWar in literature. 4aFrieden/i.d. Literatur. 4aKrieg/i.d. Literatur. 4aMittelalter/Literatur. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aWar and Peace in Literature (Medieval and Early Modern Times).1 aArabatzis, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreeze, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasey, Denis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCollette, Carolyn P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnell, Charles W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDempsey, John A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuwa, Yuri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrimbert, Joan Tasker, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolder, Heidi J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Angus J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKocher, Zan, eco